# DashLink Backend — Comprehensive Implementation Plan v2

> **Source**: [DashLink PRD v1.0](file:///Users/tolusmith/Documents/dashlink/DashLink_PRD_v1.pdf)
> **Stack**: FastAPI (Python 3.12+) · PostgreSQL 16 · Redis 7 · SQLAlchemy 2.0 + Alembic · Celery · Docker
> **Architecture**: Module-Based (Vertical Slice) Monolith

---

## 1. Architecture Philosophy

### Module-Based (Vertical Slice) Architecture

Every domain concern lives in a **self-contained module**. Each module owns its models, schemas, routes, services, and repository — no cross-module imports of internals. Modules communicate through the **shared core** or **explicit interfaces (protocols)**.

```
Module = Routes + Schemas + Service + Repository + Models
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Why vertical slices, not layers?** In a traditional layered architecture, a single feature change touches files across 4–5 directories. With modules, all related code lives together — easier to reason about, test, refactor, and eventually extract into a microservice.

### CAP Theorem Trade-offs

DashLink is a commerce platform that handles **money and inventory**. We make deliberate CAP trade-offs per subsystem:

| Subsystem | CAP Choice | Rationale |
|-----------|-----------|-----------|
| **Payments & Stock** | **CP** (Consistency + Partition tolerance) | Payments and inventory MUST be consistent. We sacrifice availability briefly (retry/queue) rather than risk double-charging or overselling. Atomic DB transactions, Redis distributed locks with fencing tokens, idempotent webhook processing. |
| **Orders** | **CP** | Order state machine transitions are strictly consistent. Serializable isolation on status updates. Optimistic locking with version columns. |
| **Analytics & Events** | **AP** (Availability + Partition tolerance) | Analytics can tolerate eventual consistency. Events are fire-and-forget to Redis/Celery, aggregated asynchronously. A few seconds of delay is acceptable. |
| **Notifications** | **AP** | Notifications are best-effort with retry. A delayed notification is acceptable; a lost payment is not. |
| **Sessions & Cache** | **AP** | Redis-backed sessions are ephemeral. Loss of a session means re-auth, not data loss. |
| **User Auth** | **CP** | Credential validation must be consistent. We never serve stale auth state. Token revocation is synchronous against Redis. |

**Implementation patterns:**
- **CP systems**: Use PostgreSQL transactions with `SERIALIZABLE` or `REPEATABLE READ` isolation, `SELECT ... FOR UPDATE`, and version columns for optimistic concurrency
- **AP systems**: Use async Celery tasks, Redis pub/sub, eventual consistency with idempotent consumers

### SOLID Principles

| Principle | How We Enforce It |
|-----------|------------------|
| **S** — Single Responsibility | Each module's `service.py` handles only its domain logic. Repositories handle only data access. Routes handle only HTTP concerns (validation, auth, response shaping). |
| **O** — Open/Closed | Payment gateways are added by implementing a `PaymentGateway` Protocol — no modification of existing gateway code. Notification channels follow the same pattern. |
| **L** — Liskov Substitution | All gateway implementations (Stripe, Paystack, Flutterwave) are interchangeable behind the `PaymentGateway` Protocol. Any can be swapped without changing checkout logic. |
| **I** — Interface Segregation | Services depend on narrow Protocols, not fat classes. e.g., `StockLocker` Protocol exposes only `lock()`, `unlock()`, `verify()` — not the entire Redis client. |
| **D** — Dependency Inversion | Services depend on abstractions (Protocols), not concrete implementations. Injected via FastAPI's `Depends()` system. Testing uses mock implementations. |

### DRY Principle Enforcement

| Pattern | Purpose |
|---------|---------|
| **`core/` shared module** | Base model classes, common schemas (pagination, error responses), security utilities, encryption — used by all modules. |
| **Repository base class** | `BaseRepository[T]` with generic CRUD (`create`, `get`, `list`, `update`, `soft_delete`). Each module's repository extends this, adding domain-specific queries only. |
| **Schema mixins** | `TimestampMixin`, `PaginatedResponse[T]`, `AuditFields` — reusable across all modules. |
| **Middleware** | Auth, rate limiting, CORS, error handling — applied globally, not duplicated per route. |
| **Protocol-based integrations** | One `PaymentGateway` Protocol, one `NotificationChannel` Protocol, one `StorageBackend` Protocol — shared contracts, multiple implementations. |

