## 7. Cross-Module Communication Patterns

Modules don't import each other's internals. Instead:

```mermaid
graph LR
    A[Checkout Module] -->|"creates order via"| B[Orders Module]
    A -->|"calls"| C[Stock Locker]
    A -->|"calls via Protocol"| D[Payment Gateway]
    D -->|"webhook triggers"| E[Payments Module]
    E -->|"emits event"| F[Notifications Module]
    E -->|"updates"| B
    G[Studio Module] -->|"calls via Protocol"| H[AI Provider]
    G -->|"calls via Protocol"| I[Storage Backend]
    J[Products Module] -->|"calls via Protocol"| I
```

**Inter-module patterns:**
1. **Direct service injection** — Module A injects Module B's service via `Depends()` (only for tightly coupled flows like checkout → order)
2. **Events / Celery tasks** — Loose coupling for side effects (payment confirmed → send notification)
3. **Shared Protocols** — Never depend on concrete implementations

---

## 8. Docker Compose (Development)

```yaml
services:
  api:
    build: .
    ports: ["8000:8000"]
    env_file: .env
    depends_on: [postgres, redis]
    volumes: ["./app:/app/app"]
    command: uvicorn app.main:app --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8000 --reload

  postgres:
    image: postgres:16-alpine
    environment:
      POSTGRES_DB: dashlink
      POSTGRES_USER: dashlink
      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: dashlink_dev
    ports: ["5432:5432"]
    volumes: ["pgdata:/var/lib/postgresql/data"]

  redis:
    image: redis:7-alpine
    ports: ["6379:6379"]

  celery_worker:
    build: .
    env_file: .env
    depends_on: [postgres, redis]
    command: >
      celery -A app.tasks.celery_app worker -l info
      -Q default,notifications,media,ai,analytics,payments

  celery_beat:
    build: .
    env_file: .env
    depends_on: [postgres, redis]
    command: celery -A app.tasks.celery_app beat -l info

volumes:
  pgdata:
```

---

## 9. Phased Execution Roadmap

### Phase 1: Foundation (Weeks 1–4) ← **START HERE**

| Week | Focus | Deliverables |
|------|-------|-------------|
| **1** | Project Setup & Auth | FastAPI scaffold (module-based), Docker Compose, `core/` module (base model, base repo, security, protocols). Auth module: register, login, JWT, Argon2. Alembic migrations. pytest setup. |
| **2** | Product Engine | Products module: CRUD, slug gen, image upload → S3/R2, Pillow pipeline, status machine, stock management. |
| **3** | Checkout & Payment | Checkout module: stock locking (Redis + DB). Payments module: Stripe + Paystack gateways (test mode), webhook handlers, HMAC verification, idempotent processing. |
| **4** | Orders & Notifications | Orders module: lifecycle, status machine, seller/buyer views. Notifications module: Resend email + Firebase push. Celery setup. |

### Phase 2: MVP Launch (Weeks 5–8)

| Week | Deliverables |
|------|-------------|
| **5** | Mobile API polish, FCM token registration, share link generation |
| **6** | **Studio module**: title/description/caption generation (OpenAI), background removal (Remove.bg), image generation (DALL·E), usage tracking |
| **7** | Buyer accounts: shadow accounts, progressive creation, saved addresses. Storefront module: `/@slug` public pages |
| **8** | MFA (TOTP), WhatsApp notifications, production deploy, security audit, load testing |

### Phase 3: Growth (Weeks 9–14)

Analytics, CRM, product variants, discount codes, bulk CSV, team RBAC, reviews, KYC, disputes, fraud scoring.

### Phase 4: Platform Maturity (Weeks 15–20)

Subscription billing, advanced AI (smart pricing, predictive stock), public API, developer docs, Zapier connectors.

---

## 10. Verification Plan

### Automated Tests
```bash
pytest tests/ -v --cov=app --cov-report=term-missing
```

Per-module test structure mirrors the module layout. Each module has:
- **Unit tests**: Service logic (stock locking, fee calc, slug gen, usage limits)
- **Integration tests**: API endpoints via `httpx.AsyncClient`
- **Mock-based tests**: Gateway Protocols mocked for deterministic testing

### Manual Verification
- End-to-end checkout flow (Stripe/Paystack test mode)
- Image upload + processing pipeline
- Studio: generate title/description/caption, verify output quality
- Webhook delivery via gateway CLI tools
- Load test with `k6` before MVP launch

---

> [!IMPORTANT]
> This plan uses **module-based vertical slice architecture** where each domain is self-contained. CAP trade-offs are explicitly chosen per subsystem (CP for payments/stock, AP for analytics/notifications). SOLID is enforced via Protocols and dependency injection. DRY is enforced via `BaseModel`, `BaseRepository`, and shared Protocols. The **AI Studio** is a first-class module enabling sellers to generate product images, titles, descriptions, and captions.
>
> Ready to execute **Phase 1, Week 1** on your approval.
